        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Washington D. C.<lb/></p>
            <p>April 11&#44; 1877<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev S. Morais<lb/>
                Philadelphia&#44; Pa.<lb/>
                Dear and Rev Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>A friend has written<lb/> me of a beautiful sermon of yours<lb/> on Sabbath before last wherein you<lb/> were pleased to speak of my<lb/> humble services on the altar of<lb/> humanity.<lb/></p>
            <p>Such remembrance&#45;&#45;<lb/>such kind and thoughtful remem&#45;<lb/>brance and recognition <hi rend="underline">now</hi> after<lb/> all the terrible years of suffering<lb/> and trial in that dark Da&#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/>land&#44; deeply touches me.<lb/></p>
            <p>It proves there will always be<lb/> some noble minds whose dumb<lb/> cold forgetfulness will not<lb/> effect&#44; some true hearts that<lb/> will bear faithfully on to<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>the last.  I should be delighted<lb/> to have a copy of that sermon<lb/> to send to my children in a<lb/> far off land.  I trust like<lb/> others of your noble and<lb/> eloquent and classically<lb/> beautiful discourses it may<lb/> appear in print.<lb/></p>
            <p>Let me however at least<lb/> thank you for your kind<lb/> cheer and pray God to<lb/> render me ever worthy<lb/> of the love and confidence<lb/> of such men as yourself.<lb/></p>
            <p>Accept the assurance<lb/> of my highest esteem and<lb/> believe me ever.<lb/></p>
            <p>Faithfully<lb/>
                your friend<lb/>
                Benj. F. Peixotto<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
